Project Objective
Design and build a simplified, single-site Electrical Power Monitoring System (EPMS) for a simulated data center. The project will demonstrate a complete industrial automation stack, including simulated electrical equipment, MQTT-based data transport, an Ignition scale-out architecture, reusable equipment models, historical data storage, alarming, visualization, scripting, containerized infrastructure, and source control.

The system is intended as a focused hobby and learning project rather than a detailed electrical-engineering model. Its purpose is to represent the essential operation and monitoring of a data center power-distribution system while remaining small enough to complete and polish.

Simulated Electrical System
The initial system will contain the following major equipment:

One utility or switchyard source
One main switchgear lineup
One standby generator
One UPS system
Two or three power distribution units
Several remote switchboards, or RSBs
A small number of feeders or ways beneath each distribution device
Each equipment type will expose only its most important operating and power-monitoring tags. Typical values will include:

Device availability and communication status
Breaker or operating state
Voltage, current, frequency and power factor
Real power in kW and apparent power in kVA
Energy consumption in kWh
Capacity and load percentage
Alarm and fault status
Generator fuel, runtime and start status
UPS load, battery charge, runtime and bypass status
The simulator will maintain realistic relationships between devices. Downstream feeder loads will roll up into their parent RSBs, PDUs, UPS and switchgear rather than behaving as unrelated random values.

Technical Architecture
The project will use a containerized, scale-out architecture managed with Docker Compose.

Equipment Simulator
	↓
MQTT Broker
	↓
Ignition Backend / Tag Provider
	↓
Ignition Perspective Frontend
	↓
SQL Historian Database
Ignition UDTs will represent the reusable equipment models. MQTT topics and tag paths will follow the same equipment hierarchy so that additional devices can be added with minimal configuration.

The system will include:

Ignition Perspective
Ignition UDTs and tag event scripting
MQTT broker and structured topic namespace
SQL database for tag history and application data
Alarm configuration and alarm history
Docker Compose infrastructure
Git and GitHub source control
Configuration files and project documentation stored with the code
User Interface
The Perspective application will contain no more than five primary screens:

Facility Overview
Simplified electrical one-line, total demand, source status, active alarms and major equipment health.
Alarm Status
Active alarms, acknowledged alarms, alarm history, severity and equipment filters.
Distribution Detail
Switchgear, UPS and major distribution measurements, breaker states, capacity and phase conditions.
PDU / RSB Detail
Reusable drill-down screen showing the selected device, its feeders, utilization and recent trends.
Generator or Energy History
Generator operating details or facility-level historical demand, energy consumption and peak-load trends.
Popups may provide additional detail without increasing the primary screen count.

Simulation Strategy
The recommended first phase is an Ignition-native simulator using memory tags and gateway scripts. This will minimize dependencies and allow the UDTs, MQTT structure, alarms, historian and Perspective application to be developed quickly.

The simulation should be implemented as a separate logical layer rather than embedding random-value expressions throughout the UDTs. A central simulation script should calculate device states, load profiles, rollups and fault scenarios.

A second-phase enhancement may replace the internal simulator with a standalone C# Modbus TCP simulator. This would create a more realistic external-device boundary and provide additional experience with protocol mapping, communication failures and independent service deployment. It should remain an optional extension rather than a requirement for the initial release.

Initial Success Criteria
The first complete version will be considered successful when it can:

Start the full infrastructure through Docker Compose
Simulate normal data center electrical operation
Publish or transport equipment data through MQTT
Instantiate reusable UDTs for each equipment class
Display live equipment status through Perspective
Generate and acknowledge realistic alarms
Store and trend historical power data
Simulate at least three operating scenarios, including normal load, utility failure and feeder overload
Rebuild the project from documented source-controlled configuration
Scope Guidance
Prioritize a small, complete and reusable system over a large device count. Begin with approximately five equipment classes, two or three PDUs or RSBs and three to five feeders per distribution device. Avoid detailed protection logic, advanced load-flow calculations, complex redundancy and predictive analytics until the core architecture is stable.

The final result should demonstrate a compact but complete industrial application: infrastructure, simulation, communications, equipment modeling, backend logic, historian, alarming and a polished operator interface.